The plain stack handles the *matching* family: every "open" is a promise that must be kept by the **most recent** unmatched partner. Valid Parentheses is the canonical form — memorize this template, because Simplify Path, Decode String, and Remove Adjacent Duplicates are all the same skeleton with different push/pop rules.

> [!ANALOGY]
> Think of nested function calls: when a function returns, it must be the **innermost** one still running — you can't return from `main` while a helper is mid-flight. Brackets work the same way: a closer must match the most recently opened, still-unclosed bracket. LIFO is not a convenience here; it *is* the problem's structure.

```cpp
bool validParentheses(const string& s) {
    stack<char> st;
    unordered_map<char,char> match = {{')','('}, {']','['}, {'}','{'}};
    for (char c : s) {
        if (c=='(' || c=='[' || c=='{') {
            st.push(c);                 // open bracket: wait for its partner
        } else {                        // close bracket: must match top
            if (st.empty() || st.top() != match[c]) return false;
            st.pop();                   // matched — resolved
        }
    }
    return st.empty();                  // nothing left waiting
}
```

[[fig:m03-bracket-match]]

> [!PITFALL]
> Two bugs kill this in OAs: (1) calling `st.top()` on an empty stack — undefined behavior in C++, so the `st.empty()` guard comes **first** in the condition; input `")("` exposes it. (2) Returning `true` at the end instead of `st.empty()` — input `"((("` finishes the loop happily but leaves three opens waiting, and must fail.

A **monotonic stack** is a plain stack with one extra rule: its contents stay sorted (increasing or decreasing from bottom to top). When a new element would break that order, you **pop** — and the moment of popping is exactly when the popped element's answer arrives.

> [!INTUITION] Who resolves whom?
> Picture people in a line, each waiting to spot the first taller person to their right. Short people keep waiting; when a tall person walks in, they resolve *everyone* shorter who was still waiting — all at once, most recent first. The stack holds exactly the still-waiting people, and they're automatically in decreasing height order (anyone shorter than a neighbor below them would already have been resolved... by someone taller in between — impossible, or they'd both be gone).

Store **indices**, not values — you almost always need the position to compute distances or index back into the array. Then decide the pop condition with one question: *"while the stack top is worse than the current element, the current element is the answer for the top."*

```cpp
// Next Greater Element to the RIGHT for every index.
// ans[i] = value of the first element to the right of i that is > nums[i], else -1.
vector<int> nextGreater(const vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();
    vector<int> ans(n, -1);
    stack<int> st;                      // holds INDICES, values strictly decreasing top->bottom
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        // current nums[i] resolves every waiting index smaller than it
        while (!st.empty() && nums[st.top()] < nums[i]) {
            ans[st.top()] = nums[i];    // nums[i] is the next-greater for st.top()
            st.pop();
        }
        st.push(i);                     // i now waits for ITS next-greater
    }
    return ans;                         // indices still on stack keep -1
}
```

[[fig:m03-nge-pop]]

> [!EXAMPLE] Trace `[2,1,5,6,2,3]`
> `i=0`: stack empty → push 0. `i=1`: 1 < 2, no pop → push 1. Stack `[0,1]`, values 2,1 — decreasing.
> `i=2` (value 5): 5 > 1 → pop 1, `ans[1]=5`; 5 > 2 → pop 0, `ans[0]=5`; push 2.
> `i=3` (value 6): pops 2, `ans[2]=6`; push 3. `i=4` (value 2): push. `i=5` (value 3): 3 > 2 → pop 4, `ans[4]=3`; push 5.
> Final: `ans = [5,5,6,-1,3,-1]` — indices 3 and 5 never met anything greater.

> [!KEY] Amortized $O(n)$
> Yes, there's a `while` inside the `for` — but each index is pushed exactly once and popped at most once, so total work is $O(n)$. Say this out loud in interviews; the amortized argument is exactly what they're listening for.

deepdives.answer:
**Why the naive approach fails.** For each bar you could expand left and right while neighboring bars are ≥ its height — that's $O(n^2)$, and with $n$ up to $10^5$ it times out. The waste in the brute force: you keep *recomputing* the same boundaries over and over.

> [!INTUITION] Fix the shortest bar
> Every rectangle under the skyline is capped by *some* shortest bar. So flip the search: for each bar `i`, ask "what's the biggest rectangle in which **this** bar is the shortest one?" Its width is bounded by the **previous smaller** bar on the left and the **next smaller** bar on the right. Trying every bar as the cap covers every candidate rectangle — nothing is missed.

Width = `right_smaller - left_smaller - 1`, area = `height[i] * width`.

**The one-pass trick.** A single left-to-right sweep with a **monotonic increasing stack of indices** finds *both* boundaries at the same instant. When bar `i` is about to break the increasing order (`h[i] < h[st.top()]`), that means `i` is the **next-smaller-to-the-right** for the popped bar — and after popping, the **new stack top** is its **previous-smaller-to-the-left**. So the popped bar's full width is known the moment it pops.

[[fig:m03-histogram-cap]]

```cpp
int largestRectangleArea(vector<int>& h) {
    int n = h.size(), best = 0;
    stack<int> st;                      // indices, heights strictly increasing bottom->top
    for (int i = 0; i <= n; ++i) {
        int cur = (i == n) ? 0 : h[i];  // sentinel 0 flushes the whole stack at the end
        while (!st.empty() && h[st.top()] > cur) {
            int height = h[st.top()]; st.pop();
            // right boundary = i (first smaller to the right)
            // left boundary  = st.top() after pop (first smaller to the left), or -1
            int leftBound = st.empty() ? -1 : st.top();
            int width = i - leftBound - 1;
            best = max(best, height * width);
        }
        st.push(i);
    }
    return best;
}
```

> [!KEY] Why the sentinel matters
> The trailing `cur = 0` (when `i == n`) is guaranteed smaller than every real bar, so it forces every remaining bar to pop and be measured. Without it, a strictly increasing histogram never pops anything and you return 0. This sentinel/flush idiom recurs across monotonic-stack problems — internalize it.

**Complexity.** $O(n)$ time — each index is pushed once and popped at most once — and $O(n)$ space.

**What generalizes.** Maximal Rectangle is literally this problem run once per matrix row (build a histogram of consecutive 1s above each cell, take the max over rows). And the "pop reveals both smaller neighbors" move is the engine behind Sum of Subarray Minimums too.

**Why one naive idea fails.** "For each index, water = `min(maxLeft, maxRight) - height`" is correct, but recomputing `maxLeft`/`maxRight` per index is $O(n^2)$. Prefix-max/suffix-max arrays fix that in $O(n)$ — but the *stack* version teaches a different, transferable idea: instead of measuring water **column by column**, fill it **layer by layer, horizontally**.

> [!INTUITION] Three roles at pop time
> Keep a **decreasing** stack of indices. Water gets trapped the moment you see a bar *taller* than the stack top: the current bar is the **right wall**, the popped bar is the **floor** of a horizontal slab, and the new top (after popping) is the **left wall**. One pop = one rectangular slab of water, fully measured.

Step by step, when `height[i] > height[st.top()]`:

1. Pop the floor: `bottom = st.top()`.
2. If the stack is now empty there's no left wall — stop (water spills out the left).
3. Left wall = new `st.top()`, right wall = `i`.
4. Bounded height of this slab = `min(height[left], height[i]) - height[bottom]`.
5. Width = `i - left - 1`. Add `bounded * width`.

[[fig:m03-water-slab]]

```cpp
int trap(vector<int>& h) {
    int n = h.size(), water = 0;
    stack<int> st;                      // indices, heights decreasing bottom->top
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        while (!st.empty() && h[i] > h[st.top()]) {
            int bottom = st.top(); st.pop();
            if (st.empty()) break;      // no left wall
            int left = st.top();
            int bounded = min(h[left], h[i]) - h[bottom];
            water += bounded * (i - left - 1);
        }
        st.push(i);
    }
    return water;
}
```

**Complexity.** $O(n)$ time, $O(n)$ space — the usual push-once/pop-once argument.

> [!EXAM]
> The two-pointer solution is $O(1)$ space and often preferred in interviews — know **both**, and volunteer the tradeoff: "the stack view fills horizontal layers in one pass; two pointers get the same $O(n)$ with constant space by moving the side with the smaller max inward." Naming the alternative is free credit.

**Why the naive approach fails.** There are $O(n^2)$ subarrays; enumerating each and taking its min is $O(n^2)$ or worse — too slow, and it's also the wrong *mental frame*.

> [!KEY] Flip the question
> Instead of "for each subarray, what's its min?", ask **"for each element, in how many subarrays is IT the minimum?"** Each such subarray contributes `nums[i]` to the total, so `answer = Σ nums[i] × (number of subarrays where nums[i] is the min)`. This "contribution of each element as a range extremum" reframe is one of the highest-leverage tricks in the whole prep.

**Counting the subarrays.** Element `i` is the minimum of a subarray exactly when the subarray extends left no further than the **previous strictly-smaller** element, and right no further than the **next smaller-or-equal** element. If `left` = number of valid start positions and `right` = number of valid end positions, then `i` is the min of `left × right` subarrays — starts and ends combine independently.

[[fig:m03-contribution-span]]

> [!PITFALL] The asymmetric boundary is the crux
> Strict `<` on one side, `<=` on the other. With duplicates (say two equal 2s), a subarray containing both minimums must be credited to **exactly one** of them: the asymmetry hands it to the leftmost. Strict on both sides counts it zero times; non-strict on both sides counts it twice. Test with `[2,2,2]`: the answer should be $2 \times 6 = 12$ (six subarrays, min always 2).

Both boundary arrays come from monotonic stacks — one forward pass (pop on `>` for previous *strictly* smaller) and one backward pass (pop on `>=` for next smaller-*or-equal*):

```cpp
// left[i]: # of contiguous elements ending at i where nums[i] is the min (using > to pop => strict left)
// right[i]: same to the right (using >= to pop => non-strict right, breaks ties)
long long sumSubarrayMins(vector<int>& a) {
    const long long MOD = 1e9+7;
    int n = a.size();
    vector<long long> left(n), right(n);
    stack<int> st;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {                 // previous strictly smaller
        while (!st.empty() && a[st.top()] > a[i]) st.pop();
        left[i] = st.empty() ? i + 1 : i - st.top();
        st.push(i);
    }
    while (!st.empty()) st.pop();
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; --i) {            // next smaller-or-equal
        while (!st.empty() && a[st.top()] >= a[i]) st.pop();
        right[i] = st.empty() ? n - i : st.top() - i;
        st.push(i);
    }
    long long ans = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
        ans = (ans + a[i] * left[i] % MOD * right[i]) % MOD;
    return ans;
}
```

**Complexity.** $O(n)$ time, $O(n)$ space.

**What generalizes.** The same contribution template solves sum of subarray **maximums** (flip comparisons), sum of subarray ranges (max − min: run it twice and subtract), and a family of "aggregate over all subarrays" OA questions. Master it here and those become five-minute problems.
